    {
      "step_id": "445d9ded",
      "step_index": 2,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "### Key functional groups / motifs\n- **Tertiary aliphatic amine**: `N(CCCC)CCCC` (a **di-n-butyl** tertiary amine)\n  - Strong **basic center**; likely **protonated (cationic)** at pH 7.4.\n- **Two aromatic rings / fused heteroaromatic system**\n  - A **benzofuran-like fused ring** (`c1oc2ccc...cc2c1`) = planar hydrophobic/aromatic domain.\n  - A **phenyl ring** (`c1ccc(... )cc1`) attached via a **carbonyl**.\n- **Aryl ketone**: `...c1C(=O)c1ccc...` (adds rigidity/planarity; H-bond acceptor).\n- **Sulfonamide**: `NS(C)(=O)=O` attached to aromatic ring\n  - Strongly polar; typically **not basic**; can be H-bond donor/acceptor; may reduce permeability somewhat but doesn\u2019t remove lipophilic bulk.\n- **Ether linker**: `OCCCN...` connecting aromatic ring to the tertiary amine (3-carbon spacer).",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:59:26.773079+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "611a1dea",
      "step_index": 3,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "### Overall physicochemical \u201cshape\u201d\n- **Classic hERG pharmacophore pattern**: **cationic center + multiple hydrophobic/aromatic regions** separated by a flexible linker.\n- Likely **high lipophilicity** (two butyls + butyl substituent + 2 aromatic systems) with one cationic center \u2192 strong tendency to partition into membranes and access the channel cavity.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:59:26.773103+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "194663b0",
      "step_index": 4,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "### Structural alerts\n- **Tertiary amine + aromatic systems**: common hERG liability motif.\n- **Terfenadine-like pattern** (not identical, but similar \u201cbulky hydrophobe\u2013linker\u2013basic center\u201d topology).\n- Not a piperidine, but the **tertiary dialkylamine** can play the same electrostatic role.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:59:26.773125+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "5e7004bd",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "## 2) SAR REASONING (why these features matter for hERG)",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:59:26.773146+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "e5f1e71d",
      "step_index": 6,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "hERG blockers often have:\n1) **A protonatable basic nitrogen** to form electrostatic interactions (and/or cation\u2013\u03c0) in the inner cavity.\n2) **Aromatic/hydrophobic groups** that bind into hydrophobic pockets and engage \u03c0-stacking with channel residues.\n3) **Appropriate spacing** (often ~4\u20137 \u00c5 effective separation) between the cation and aromatic features, plus conformational adaptability.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:59:26.773168+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "bf1648c0",
      "step_index": 7,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "This molecule matches all three:\n- The **tertiary amine** will be **mostly protonated**, enabling strong attraction to the channel cavity environment and key residues.\n- The molecule has **two sizeable aromatic domains** (benzofuran-like fused ring + phenyl), providing **\u03c0/hydrophobic surface** for binding.\n- The **O\u2013CH2\u2013CH2\u2013CH2\u2013N** tether gives a **flexible \u201creach\u201d** from the aromatic ring to the cationic center, allowing conformations that place the charged N and aromatic rings in the geometry hERG favors.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:59:26.773189+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "6ce92ad0",
      "step_index": 8,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "The **sulfonamide** increases polarity and may reduce passive permeability somewhat, but in many known hERG blockers, adding one polar group does **not** eliminate blockade if the compound remains (a) cationic and (b) sufficiently hydrophobic.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:59:26.773210+00:00"
    },
    {
